  "prompt": "What causes a sonic boom?",
  "response": "A sonic boom is caused when an object moves through the air at a speed faster than the speed of sound. This speed is known as the \"sound barrier\" and is approximately 343 meters per second (1,235 kilometers/hour or 767 miles/hour) at sea level under standard conditions. When an object, such as a supersonic aircraft, travels faster than sound, it compresses the air molecules in front of it, creating shock waves. These shock waves coalesce and form a single, powerful shock wave that travels to the ground, creating the loud noise known as a sonic boom.\n\nThe sound is similar to the pressure wave created in front of a speeding boat pushing water aside, but in the case of a sonic boom, the air pressure causes a rapid change, resulting in the explosive sound. The boom is heard as a sudden onset of sound waves produced when the shock wave passes by an observer and can create significant disturbances, such as rattling windows and causing objects to shake. The intensity and reach of the sonic boom depend on various factors, including the size, shape, and speed of the aircraft, its altitude, and atmospheric conditions.",
